title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec KSG 12g shotgun 12 gauge 14 round Black
postcontent: he KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1 inch overall length and an 18.5 inch cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3 inch rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1.75 inch up to the 3 inch..This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. .The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. .The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward. Specification: Caliber 12 gauge 3 inch ,Barrel length 18.5 inch,Total capacity 6+6+1,Weight empty 6.9 lbs,Weight loaded 8.5 lbs,Length 26.1 inch,Height 7 inch,Condition is Factory New and will ship to FFL dealer.

title: For Sale:  FN Five Seven 5.7 DA with Ammo, First Edition..Rare
postcontent: For sale is an EXCELLENT CONDITION, Extremely RARE Original, FIRST edition, FN Five Seven 5.7 Double-Action Only (DAO) pistol, Imported year 1999. The serial number is silk-screened onto the frame above the grip. The FN Five-seven DAO pistols were not sold to the public!!! The first variant Five-seven DAO pistol was originally restricted by FN to law enforcement and military customers use ONLY. It is double-action only with a trigger pull of 4.5 to 6.5 daN (10 to 14 lbf) and NO manual safety device. It has a pebbled grip pattern, smoothly-contoured accessory rail, low profile fixed sights and a circular-shaped trigger guard designed to improve gloved use. It does not have a slide release and the slide is not serrated as on newer variants, but a portion of the slide is instead slightly concave to aid grasping. The original Five-seven pistols were shipped with only two (2) 20 round magazines. These mags will NOT work in later Five-seven IOM or USG variant unless the magazine safety has been removed or deactivated. This pistol comes in the original FNH hard case with operator’s instructions/manual, cleaning kit, and (2) 20 round magazines. PLUS ~ 500 rounds SS198LF LEO/Military Ammo (10 boxes).

title: For Sale:  MAS 49/56 Rifle in 7.5x54 French
postcontent: Up for sale is a MAS-49/56, a French made battle rifle. This firearm is known for its ruggedness and reliability, designed to operate from the sands of Algeria to the jungles of Vietnam. Mechanically this is a very simple rifle, field stripping with just a button push for easy maintenance. Internally it reminds me of an SKS, very straightforward and easy to understand.This rifle is chambered in the original 7.5 French round, so it is without the functional issues that the rifles converted to .308 by Century are infamous for. It is in very good shape with some wear here and there from use, but functions fine, including the gas regulator for the grenade launcher. Ammo can be a bit tough come by unless you order online or have a Cabela's nearby, so I'm including 100 rounds of PPU 7.5 French to get you started. A shooter who reloads their own ammo would do well with this rifle. Also included is the original 10 round magazine.Updated: Found two more boxes of ammo in my pile, 100 rounds total with rifle.

title: For Sale:  Enfield No4 Mk1T sniper made by Long Branch in 1945
postcontent: This No4 Mk1* (T)sniper rifle was manufactured at the end of WWII by the Long Branch Arsenal during 1945 which manufactured a total of only 992 No4 Mk1* T's. It has matching serial numbers on the receiver, magazine, forearm and bolt. It has an excellent 25 inch 5 grooved bore with bright and sharp lands. The headspace is good on a 0.067" armourers gauge with a No '3' bolt head. The firing pin protrusion is 0.045 inch. The action is very good, tight and clean. The metal shows 99% of the blue finish with a little wear on the edges. It has a good BLO finish to the walnut stock with no cracks or major dings. The butt stock is stamped with the serial number of the scope it was set up with (1890 over another which is illegible). The scope mounts are original with no indications of the screws being re-locked (piened). The scope was produced by REL (Research Enterprises Ltd) with excellent optics and adjustments, complete with original leather lens cover with the broad arrow marking (maybe British as most Canadian equipment was marked C broad arrow). This appears to have been refurbished. Some witness marks of usage on the tube from the leather scope cups are present. The REL scopes were thought by some to be superior quality to the British scopes. The Brits may be excused as they were being bombed during production by the Germans. The wood forearm and hand guards are dark walnut wood. The rear hand guard has a arsenal repair applied at the rear. The butt stock is lighter in color and is stamped and painted with numerous numbers. The cheek piece appears to be of oak wood. This rifle has seen service in the Far East WWII theatre (India) from little patches of green paint on the metal which they used as a secondary protective. It has a serialized standard ten round magazine. This excellent condition is commensurate with one of the WW II Enfields' which has seventy years service. This will complete a collection with a rare Long Branch sniper..........no  tradesplease contact me    @     REDACTED

postcontent: This is a service grade 1955 Springfield (SA) Armory M1 Garand; the rifle that General George S. Patton referred to as: " the greatest battlefield implement ever devised." She was purchased through the Civilian Marksmanship Program. The rifle is chambered in the venerable 30-06 cartridge. The SA barrel dates to 4-55. The SA rifle serial number dates to 1955 as well. That, along with like condition and Patina, suggests the barrel is original to the gun. The serial number will be given upon phone conversation only. There are no visible import marks. The stainless gas seal is the only area exhibiting any significant wear. Rust is non-existent, nor are there any signs of major battle scars. Normal wear is minimal for the time frame. There is evidence of a faint ordnance cartouche stamp on the stock just below the left side of receiver.  The barrel is shiny and remains accurate. The rifle functions wonderfully and is accompanied by 5 en bloc clips.  The rifle wears an OD nylon sling, befitting of the time period in both use and appearance. The weapon has the normal matching of the major US manufacturers parts of that time:Receiver- SABarrel- SA 4-1955Trigger Group- International Harvester Op Rod- SA Bolt- Harrington and RichardsonSights (SA). The sights are in excellent mechanical condition and show minimal wear. They remain audible, tactile and precise on the firing line.This Garand is an excellent example of American Ingenuity.
